    "source": "_Types_and_Processing_Methods_of_Rice_in_Grain_Stu",
    "contenu": "The document provides detailed information on different types of rice and related processing methods. It is part of a larger text on \"The Grains, or Cereals\" and includes descriptions of aromatic rices, pigmented rices, and various forms of processed rice like brown and parboiled rice. Below is a structured representation of the key points mentioned:\n\n### Rice Types and Characteristics:\n\n#### 1. General Attributes of Rice:\n- **Stickiness:** Some rice varieties disintegrate when cooked and are often soaked and then steamed.\n- **Sweetness:** Commonly not sweet, used for making desserts in Asia.\n- **Standard Variety:** The default rice in countries like Laos and northern Thailand.\n\n#### 2. Aromatic Rices:\n- **Grain Type:** Long- and medium-grain varieties that accumulate unusual concentrations of volatile compounds.\n- **Examples:** Indian and Pakistani basmati, Thai jasmine, and U.S. Della.\n- **Characteristics:** These varieties usually have low amylose.\n\n#### 3. Pigmented Rices:\n- **Pigmentation:** Presence of anthocyanin pigments in the bran layers; most common colors are red and purple-black.\n- **Bran Treatment:** The bran may be left intact or partially milled away, leaving traces of color.\n\n#### 4. Brown Rice:\n- **Processing:** Unmilled with bran, germ, and aleurone layers intact.\n- **Characteristics:** Maintains more nutritional content due to the presence of these layers.\n\n#### 5. Parboiled or Converted Rice:\n- **History:** Used for over 2,000 years in India and Pakistan.\n- **Processing Technique:** Involves steeping in water, boiling or steaming, then drying before milling.\n- **Benefits:** Improves nutritional quality, hardens the grain, makes it less sticky, and allows for firmer cooked grains.\n\n#### Additional Diagram Explanation:\n- The diagram on the document visually distinguishes between different parts of the rice grain:\n  - **Brown Rice:** Includes the whole grain with bran, embryo, and aleurone layer.\n  - **Polished Rice:** Stripped of the bran and embryo, primarily consisting of endosperm.\n  - **Wild Rice:** Whole grain from a North American grass, characterized by a glossy appearance due to particular processing methods.\n\nThis content aids in understanding the varieties of rice, their distinct processing methods, and their impacts on flavor, texture, and nutritional value."
  },
