    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_327",
    "contenu": "The document discusses various characteristics and uses of garlic and leeks focusing on their culinary relevance.\n\n### Garlic\n\n- **Processing and Flavor**: Garlic loses moisture after harvest, becoming more intensely flavorful then gradually losing its distinct garlicky taste as it ages in storage. The peeling and chopping of garlic are tedious, but necessary to prepare it for cooking or oil preservation. The process of preserving garlic in oil can encourage bacterial growth, particularly botulism, unless preventive measures such as acid soaking are taken first. Garlic’s color may change to bluish-green due to reactions involving its sulfur compounds, but this can be minimized by blanching.\n  \n- **Garlic and Breath**: The text discusses the phenomenon of \"garlic breath,\" caused by methanethiol and other volatile compounds released in the mouth and digestive system. Garlic breath peaks several hours after consumption and can be mitigated by consuming oxidizing mouthwash or fresh fruits and vegetables that trigger browning enzymes, which help neutralize the odors. \n\n### Leeks\n\n- **Characteristics**: Unlike garlic, leeks don't form underground storage bulbs but have scallion-like leaves. They can grow quite large and have a milder, cabbage-like flavor. The white part, which gets less sunlight, is the most desirable section and can be thickened by piling soil around the growing plants.\n  \n- **Usage**: Leeks require thorough washing to remove dirt from between the layers. They are hardy against the cold, can be harvested through the winter, and are versatile in cooking. They offer a texture ideal for soups and stews when cooked.\n\n### General Information\n\n- **Next Topics**: The text also indicates subsequent discussion topics such as other plant stems and stalks including asparagus and celery, suggesting a broader discussion on vegetables derived from various plant parts in subsequent sections. \n\nThis structured summary covers the primary points relating to garlic and leeks, their culinary uses, handling, and specific characteristics as described in the text."
  },
