    "contenu": "The content of the document discusses pairing advice for Chardonnay, a type of wine. Here are the main points:\n\n1. **Pairing with Sharp Ingredients:**\n   - Most oak-aged Chardonnay is not well-paired with very sharp ingredients like leeks, olives, asparagus, capers, zucchini, tomatoes, and broccoli rabe. However, unoaked or sharper Chardonnay examples can pair brilliantly with these ingredients.\n\n2. **Pairing with Overly Sweet Foods:**\n   - Combining oak, Chardonnay, and sugar in the mouth is generally not recommended due to an unhappy pairing outcome. Instead, it’s advisable to opt for different wines when consuming very sweet foods like those served at Easter, Thanksgiving, or dishes like Thai coconut curry.\n\n3. **Pairing in Cheese Courses:**\n   - For a cheese course, it is recommended to pair off oaky Chardonnay with specific types of cheeses to better showcase the wine. Suitable cheese choices include smooth aged Brie, Swiss Emmenthaler, French Comté, and mild creamy Italian Teleme. It is suggested to avoid pungent cheeses and those high in acid, such as goat cheese.\n\nThe document also has a footer that mentions \"CHARDONNAY 56,\" which suggests that this text is page 56 of a section or book focusing on Chardonnay."
